## Legal Exceptions and Protections

Despite the broad application of at-will employment, several exceptions exist to protect employees:

| Exception Type            | Description                                                                                          | Source                                                                                  |
|---------------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Public Policy Exception   | Prohibits termination for reasons that violate public policy (e.g., refusing to commit illegal acts) | [BrightHub, n.d.](https://www.brighthub.com/office/human-resources/articles/104220/)    |
| Discrimination Laws       | Protects employees from termination based on protected classes (race, gender, age, etc.)           | [RavenLaw, 2014](https://ravenlaw.com/news/can-employer-fire-terminate-reason/)         |
| Implied Contract          | Prevents firing if implied promises of job security exist                                          | [Wikipedia, 2023](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/At-will_employment)                     |
| Good Faith and Fair Dealing | Some states require terminations to be made in good faith and not in bad faith                      | [Paperdue, 2018](https://www.paperdue.com/essay/employment-at-will-essay-2169413)       |
| Union and Collective Bargaining Agreements | Require "just cause" for termination in unionized workplaces                                   | [Brown Firm PLLC, n.d.](https://www.brownfirmpllc.com/at-will-employment-state-meaning/) |

These exceptions illustrate that even in an at-will system, there are legal boundaries to protect employees from unfair dismissal.

